{"/service/ndnp/fu/batch_fu_immokalee_ver01/data/sn95047334/00529042474/1958022701/0114.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE FOUR\nGADSDEN COUNTY TIMES\nand continuing\nTHE CHATTAHOOCHEE TRIBUNE\nPublished each Thursday at 15 S. Madison Street\nA JOHN H. PERRY NEWSPAPER\nESTABLISHED 1901\nQuincy, Florida\nEntered m the post office at Quincy, Florida, th* Act d\nMarch 1879 as latter of the second class.\nOne Year, $3.00 Two Years, $5.50 Six Months, $1.75\nJ. L. Hutchinson Publisher\n\u00a9NATIONAL editorial\n\u2014i meiMiaMMawaM\nSuper Carrier Enterprise\nWorkers In the shipbuilding yard at Newport News,\nVirginia, recently laid the first keel section of the Navy's\nnew atomic super-carrier Enterprise.\nThe very name \"Enterprise\" brings back memories to\nall those who remember the war at sea in the Pacific in\nWorld War 11. But the new Enterprise is to be a far cry\nfrom the World War H carrier. The new Enterprise is to be\nan eighty-five thousand-ton aircraft carrier.\nWhen one recalls that the Forrestal is a sixty-thousand\nton carrier, as is the Saratoga, and that they are considered\ngiants among naval ships, the size of the Enterprise can be\nappreciated. The Enterprise is approximately the size of\nihe Queen Elizabeth, which displaces over eightyfive thous\nand tons. Until the plans for Enterprise were accepted, the\nQueen Elisabeth was the largest ship ever to be undertaken.\nThe Enterprise will be a military \"first\" in several ways.\nShe will be the largest carrier ever built, and she will be\natomic-powered. Upon her success, and the success of other\ngiant carriers like her, may depend the future of the air\ncraft carrier, and to some extent, the future security of the\n^United States.\nAs the reader probably knows, there are those who\nTjrgue that one modem bomb can sink even the largest\nwarship, and, because of this, land bases only, should be\nutilized. The Navy replies that it Is more difficult to knock\nout a moving air base than it is to knock out a fixed-to-land\nbase. Moreover, the Navy believes that its defensive weap\nons, its anti-missile missiles, and its anti-aircraft protection\nwill make these giant carriers highly difficult targets.\nIt will be three years before Enterprise is ready to make\nits bow. That means the Navy will not have the services\nof an atomic super-carrier until 1961, at the earliest. That\nwill not be a day too soon, and one can only hope that\nthe delivery date can be improved upon in view of the\ninternational situation.\nThe Trend In Weather\nThis winter has been a rugged one, as was predicted\nby at least one famous almanac, and as had been predicted\nby more than one weather expert.\nOne notable weather expert, writing in a national mag\nazine last fall, noted that sunspots indicated a return of\nbitter winters. In other words, the frequency of sunspots has\nlessened and therefore colder weather can be expected.\nMoreover, it was pointed out by this weather expert that\nweather ran in forty-year cycles. The forty-year cycle\ntoward wanner and wanner winters has just concluded,\naccording to this theory, and we are now entering a forty-\nyear cycle of colder and colder winters\u2022\nWhile we are not the final authority on weather matters,\nit seems that this winter's weather has backed up his theory\nadmirably. It has backed it up to the extent that most of\nFlorida's produce crops, and much of her citrus crops, have\nbeen ruined by several severe freezes. The sustained\nfreezing weather in the southeastern part of the country, and\nIn the southwestern regions to some extent, has been un\nusual and abnormally harsh.\nIf the expert who predicted a forty- year trend toward\ncolder and colder winters is correct, by the 1960\u2019s we will\nbe feeling the trend even more severely. By then, accord\ning to this prediction, we will be experiencing weather which\ncomes nearer the bitter winters of the 1880's than any we\n_ have seen in many years.\nTo The Moon\nIt seems to be only a question of time until man has\ntraveled to the moon. We have joked about this inevitable\ntrip on past occasions and we are still not a candidate to\nmake a trip to the moon. However, recent developments\nmake it certain that either we, or the Russians, will be firing\nrockets to the moon in the very near future.\nThe moon, strange as it may seem to some, is only about\ntwo or three days of traveling time from the earth. We are\nspeaking in terms of rocket travel. This does not mean that\na rocket will have to bum fuel and propel itself for two or\nthro* days. Such a load of fuel would be a tremendous one.\nIt should be remembered that after the rocket has clear\ned the heavy layer of gases surrounding the earth, generally\ngalled our atmosphere, then the rocket engine can be turned\n\u201coff. The rocket to the moon could travel in the same man\nner as the earth satellites now circling us, which maintain\na speed of about 18,000 m.p.h., because of the lack of resist\nance encountered in their flight.\nThis lack of resistance would be encountered by a\nrocket traveler headed to the moon, as soon as he was two\nor three hundred miles out from the earth, and he could,\nwith a good boost from that point, reach the moon in two\nor three days with a minimum of extra power needed. The\ngreatest danger, and the greatest doubt, surrounds the re\n'\u2022tum trip, and problems connected with it\n\nA Baseball Thought\nThe Los Angeles Dodgers hove now made anangements\nto use the Los Angeles Coliseum during the coming base*\nball season. This means they will have a large seating\ncapacity at their ball park, but the announcement is not a\nwelcome one among National League pitchers.\nSeveral of the finest in the League have expressed bitter\nness because the distance to the left field line from home\n\u2018plate is only 250 feet. The Dodgers have a number of right\nhanded hitters and they are expected to send the ball over\n.the fence, or wall, in left field, quite frequently.\nThe opinion of many is that a 250 feet distance is not a\nsufficient distance tor a homerun, even if the ball must clear\na barrier at that point. A cry has gone up, as a result, far\nthe standardization of the various baseball parks.\nIt seems fairly obvious that all Major League baseball\n_ parks should have uniform dimensions from home plate to\n^left and right fields. The Commissioner of baseball should\npromulgate a policy which would require this to be ac\ncomplished, within a period of years. It is not fair to the\nplayers of the different teams for one Club to have the ad\nvantage of a tailor-made home field, calculated to favor\nits particular strength.\nDR. JEKYLL AND MR. HYDROGFN\nok\nIL. O 1\nIHr m\n./wl, K\u2019- WB w\nKk \u2022fl I\n1 MWO\nw fl ImiM\n'/I A\n^KWHKLk Okl\nL IB Sim He.\nB W\nOs IO IMF o E\nFROZEN FISH IN WINTER'S DEEP FREEZE -John Macruda, engi\nneer on the fishing boat The Cushmert, surveys his frost-en\ncrusted vessel at the Fulton Fish Market pier in New York.\nThe mercury dived to 11.2 degrees in a cold wave that covered\nmost of the nation east of the Rocky Mountains. (International)\nMARRIAGEABLE PRINCESSES Posing in their banquet-batt\ngowns in Stockholm are the three marriageable granddaugh\nters of King Gustav VI and Queen Louise of Sweden. The\nPrincesses (L to r.) are: Margaretha, Brigitta and Desiree.\nPeople cause better than nine out of ten forest fires, which destroy\nthe trees of tomorrow, slow the growth rate of surviving trees,\nincrease their susceptibility to insect and disease attach, and\nmortally wound many so that they eventually die.\nGADSDEN COUNTYTIMES, QUINCY, FLORIDA, THURSDAY, FEBRUARY 27,1958\nE. H. S. REPORTS\nFROM WASHINGTON\nTha Recession\nIka's Prediction\nStill No ICBM\nReds Maintain Lead\nWashington With unemploy\nment now past the 5,000,000-\nmark, the Republican Adminis\ntration is officially concerned\nwith the deepening recession.\nThat does not mean all is des\npair. In fact, the government\u2019s\neconomists think the recession\nwill start coming to an end in\nthe very near future.\nBut, as any business prognos\nticator knows, something can\ncome along and upset the best\nof plans, and the Republican Ad\nministration is on the spot. Pres\nident Eisenhower and Republi\ncan members of the last session\nof the 85th Congress cannot af\nford any mistake on the economy\nat this point.\nThe President has gone on rec\nord as saying he thinks business\nwill be noticing a pickup by sum\nmer. Congress, with an election\nstarring members in the face in\nNovember, is chafing at the bit\non the question of taking action\nto lighten the effects of the re\ncession.\nIf the President is right and\nbusiness does turn upward by\nsummer legislative action may\nnot be necessary. But if that\nforecast is incorrect and busi\nness does not perk up, then Con\ngress will be quitting when the\ncrisis becomes most intense.\nIt might be, as Churchill once\nsaid about a tight corner in\nWorld War 11, \u201ca damned close\nrun thing.\u201d Such a tense situa\ntion, economically, has Admini\nstration officials and Republican\nCongressmen on the spot. The\nnext two or three months will be\nanxious ones, months of waiting.\nTb^ results are likely to have\nwidespread political effects, in\naddition to economic repercus\nsions. Control of Congress hinges\non the business picture as of fall,\nand there is little doubt in G. O.\nP. circles that the party\u2019s chanc\nes would be almost nil should\nthe country be in the depths of\na severe recession come Novem\nber.\nThat explains some of the\nsentiment for tax cuts in Coh\ngress, some demands that the\nfederal government spend even\nmore money in an effort to give\nbusiness a boost, and the rest\nlessness of some member over the\ngrowing unemployment lists, fal\nling tax revenues, etc.\nDespite the fact that the Unit\ned States now has an earth-satel\nlite circling the globe, there are\nindications we are a long way\nfrom having an operational ICB\nM. An we are still far behind\nthe Russians in this vital race.\nThe Air Force recently fired\nPicture yourself behind the wheel of this Plymouth Savoy\u2014it 1 s\nn\nTHE LOWEST PRICED HARDTOP\nIN THE LOW-PRICE \u201c3\nI J\nCar \u201cC\u201d costs *lO4 more-Car \u201cF\" *49 more than Plymouth*\nYou wouldn\u2019t think it possible to find so much difference\nin the prices of similar models in the low-price \u201c3\u201d!\nBut it\u2019s a fact that the long, low, graceful Plymouth\nSavoy costs far, far less than any hardtop made by\nthe \u201cother two\u201d! Just ask your Plymouth dealer to\nshow you the facts and figures.\nAnd in the Plymouth Savoy, you get features\u2014\nimportant engineering advances\u2014 that the others can\u2019t\noffer you at any price.\nYou get a revolutionary new suspension system\nas standard equipment in the Plymouth Savoy at not\none penny extra cost to you! Torsi on-Aire gives you\nthe world\u2019s smoothest ride\u2014feed at all times, with no\nnose-dive, no sway, no rolt\nSee your Plymouth dealer today-he\u2019s trading high and on your terms!\nFor cleaner, safer used cars\u2014Plymaulh TlP^OP_used carst.\nan ICBM in Florida; it failed to\ncomplete its test-run and must\nbe marked as a failure. It is\ntrue that the Air Force fired an\nICBM successfully during the\nPresident\u2019s recent trip to France,\nbut that missile was not a fully\nloaded ICBM.\nIn other words, it is doubtful\nif the United States has, or can,\nfire successfully a fully-loaded\nICBM missile to this day. The\nfirst successful Atlas firing was\nabout a 600-mile test. The ICBM\nis supposed to travel 5,000 miles.\nOne successful 600-mile firing\nof an Atlas which wasn\u2019t fully\nloaded does not constitute pos\nsession of an operational ICBM.\nThe truth is that the United\nStates still does not have one.\nWhether the Russians have one\nor not, is a matter of speculation,\nbut it is generally suspected that\nthe Russians are ahead of us.\nMoscow has announced that sev\neral have been successfully test\nfired, Usually Moscow\u2019s defense\nannouncements come after the\nevent, and not before. And there\nis no reason to believe, in this\nparticiular case, that they are\nmaking false announcements.\nIn the past their announce\nments have not revealed how far\ntheir progress has gone, and if\nthis is the case with their ICBM,\nthe Reds may be further along in\nthe production and control of\nICBM\u2019s than we think.\nMaking A Start\nIn Farm Forestry\n(EDITOR'S NOTE: This is\nanother in a series of articles by\nK. B. McClintick, farm forester\nof Gadsden County.)\nYour farm forester receives\nvaried requests from woodland\nowners interested in working\ntimber. One man may want to\nplant trees, the next man may\nwant to mark trees, and yet an\nother may want to sell every\nthing and start again.\nThe most important considera\ntion is that it may be most de\nsirable to do none or all of these\nthings, even on the same farm.\nIt is necessary to look over the\nsituation, and fit in each proced\nure where it will do the most\ngood.\nIn farm forestry this is called\nmaking a preliminary examina\ntion. No matter what the prob\nlem the best way to start good\nforestry is to consider all possi\nbilities. Examine each area and\ndecide -what would pay the most,\nnow and later.\nIf you are ready to start good\nforestry, ask for a preliminary\nexamination. It doesn\u2019t cost any\nthing to look it over. You may\nwrite to K. B. McClintick, Farm\nForester, 9 South Jackson St.,\nQuincy, Florida, or when in\nQuincy come in or call at the\noffice in the Farm Bureau build\ning, telephone MAin 7-6718.\nMcClintick is employed by the\nFlorida Forest Service to assist\nwoodland owners in Gadsden\nand Liberty counties with prob\nlems in timber management. Re\nmember good forestry doesn\u2019t\ncost it pays. Don\u2019t worry about\nyesterday Think wisely to-day\nProtect your woods from fire,\nalways.\nMAN'S BEST FRIEND\nSouthampton, England\u2014There\nis a blind purebred greyhound\nnamed Flash who has his own\nguide dog to help him about.\nFlash was half starved and blind\ned by disease when found in Lon\ndin by the Society for Preven\ntion of Cruelty to Animals.\nA newspaper story about him\natt. acted the attention of Mr.\nand Mrs. George Corbin of South\nampton. The Corbin\u2019s little fox\nterrier, Peggy, had been guiding\na blind Labrador dog down the\nstreets on daily walks. The Cor\nbins toook Flash into their home,\nand now Peggy guides both dogs.\nThe real art of living includes\nthe art of loafing.\nSears, Roebuck and Company\nSale Representative\nNeeded\nSears, Roebuck and Co. has permanent open\ning for a Home Service Representative in the\nQuincy area. Broad assortment of merchandise\nto sell including Appliances, Plumbing and\nHeating, Building Materials, Farm Equipment,\nFloor Covering, Home Furnishings, Television,\nand others. Must have car, but out of town\ntraveling is not required. Prior sales experi\nence important but not essential. Excellent op\nportunity for the right man. Many outstanding\nCompany benefits. Drawing account and com\nmission plus mileage. Adequate training to\nassure excellent income. Apply in person.\nSears, Roebuck and Company\nCorner Madison Washington Quincy, Fla.\nYou get Total-Contact Brakes\u2014safer, surer/\nsmoother\u2014exactly the same design as those used on\nAmerica\u2019s costliest car!\nYou get crowd-stopping Silver Dart Styling that\na leading auto magazine calls the newest, clean\nest design\u201d!\nYou get the biggest windshield, the greatest total\nglass area, the best visibility, and more over-all roomi\nness and comfort!\nBut just words can\u2019t describe the Plymouth Savoy\nHardtop. You\u2019ve got to see it\u2014sit inside it\u2014 drive it\nto appreciate all the advantages it offers at savings\nof from W to flO^!\nBased on factory retail prices, Detroit, Mich,\nIn the Battle of Santa Rota\nIsland in 1861, Confederates and\nFederals lost their lives. This\nentire battlefield is within Fort\nPickens State Park between old\nbrick Fort Pickens and the ponds\neast of the U. S. Coast Guard\nStation.\nPeople do not exist for the\nbenefit of institutions; it\u2019s the\nother way around.\nMail Your Contributions for\nFlorida Heart Association\nto Your Local Postmaster.\nLIQUID OR TABLETS\nGIVES \u2022SUBBtfIUUW\nFROM ALL THOSE MISERIES\n\u2022F *NARDTO*mr COLM","height":"29205","width":"20121"}}
